reviewText: I absolutely love this show! Can't wait for Season 4!
must see

Tatiana is amazing, the camera work is amazing, the writing is fantastic, the premise is fantastic, and the creativity involved with having the clones appear together is just great. Not sure of her name right offhand, but the actress that plays Tatiana's characters WITH Tatiana is one of the hardest working people in show business.
I personally fended this show off for quite some time. I figured it just couldn't be that great.
It's great enough that I've seen every episode from Seasons 1-3, several times, and I'm pre-ordering season 4, AND I have it all on blu-ray. One of my very favorite shows of all time. Not sure if I'm glad I waited or not, but it really is fantastic. There's no taking away from Tatiana's physical beauty either. But you gotta admit: Helena is the absolute best.

I realize that season 4 doesn't hit BBC America until April 14th, but I guarantee it'll be 5 stars.  No doubt in my mind.  If you haven't watched this show, you need to.  Right now.  Seriously, stop what you're doing and watch it.  As the reviewer before me said, start S1E1 and kiss your weekend good-bye.  Can you finish 3 seasons in a weekend?  Yes.  I promise that you can and you will.  Once you experience the shock and awe that comes with watching Tatiana Maslany, you'll become a craven addict and then you'll come back here and tell me how right I am.  You're welcome in advance.  ;)

OK, if you're reading this, then chances are you're going to watch Season 4 no matter what I say, particular as you know darn well that there is no way in the universe I could possibly have seen season four yet as it doesn't exist. But if you haven't seen this show, go check out season one, in my opinion one of the best shows ever made. And if you like that, continue on to season two. Season three, well, I felt there was a bit of a slump there, but I'm still hooked and still ready and eager for season four to come along. And if you like season three, well then check this one out too. FYI, only truly useful thing I can say is this. Great show, but it's a serial, and the less you know coming in the better. Start with season one, episode one and watch them in order. Good luck! And I hope you enjoy the show as much as I have.  .

The one criticism I could make for the last couple seasons of Orphan Black is that it took on more of a soap opera vibe.  I didn't really mind though, because unlike most soap opera-heavy sci fi (ie American sci fi), the acting was just extraordinary-- it was never a series about a bunch of pretty people dicking around while the world building falls to sh.  But this season, in conjunction with the fun soap opera stuff of the clones, there's also a renewed focus on the plot (the neolutionists).  The series has returned to its sci fi roots and imo it's really the complete package.

Sarah Manning, a petty criminal, witnesses a woman identical in appearance to herself, commit suicide by throwing herself at a moving train. Sarah, takes her bag, visits her apartment, and assumes her identity. Strange events occur and she uncovers the truth - there are other clones like her which were made in an experiment. Some clones are closely monitored, while some found their way out of the experiment.

The lead actor does an excellent job in playing various roles. The first and second season are really well made but I found the show to go downhill after that - too complex/exotic plot unfolds. As if the original script was made with a certain idea in mind for the first couple of seasons and then they hit a wall and had to invent some new not so well made content.

I just finished the 4th season of Orphan Black. Tatiana Maslany is an amazing actor. All of her clone characters are done so well. But the story line is getting irritating & old. Constant betrayals & really foolish alliances with sworn enemies - this is what happens on series that soon fail. I'd hate to see that happen to this one. And yes, where is Marion Bowles? I was very happy to see Michele Forbes enter, but she never made an exit - she just disappeared! How unfortunate... :(

This is one of the best series in my experience of TV history (watching since about 1953).  The primary asset is Tatiana Maslany:  Her ability to portray a dozen distinct characters, each distinctively and brilliantly acted in their own voice, look, characteristic expressions, gestures, etc. places her at the top of the actress heap.  Aside from the brilliant Ms. Maslany, the sci-fi plot, the human interaction, attraction, and conflict, are engaging and touch, if clumsily, on actual ethical considerations.  The non-Maslany actors are quite effective, although, like most actors, not Tatiana at all.

Each season of this show gets better! Tatiana Maslany of course deserves a ton of credit for its success -- I often forget that the same actor is playing such disparate characters as Alison and Helena. It just does not seem possible. This season, the Introduction of a new "sestra" and the development of the character of Beth Childs through flashbacks gave Maslany even more to work with. But other cast members were also fantastic; Art just keeps getting more soulful and intense, and this was for sure Donny's season to umm, shine? Felix is a bit absent in the early episodes as he is exploring other sides to his identity, but the introduction of a new character on that side of the plot is quite hilarious and touching as well. The season, (hope this is not a spoiler) ends on a nail-biting cliffhanger, setting us up nicely for the last and final installment slated to air on BBC America in April 2017. I can't wait, though I'll be sad when it's over.

One of the things I enjoy most about this series is the fact the writers are willing to take risks.
In Season Four they did just that by filling in back stories, using flashback sequences to great effect, and advancing the show's storyline. Because they did, we learned exactly why Det. Beth Childs committed suicide - not because she was "too brittle" or "broken" but to save her "sisters." It was an act of self sacrifice that made her character not only more appealing but also more real and her willingness to do that provides the audience with a justification for why the clones are so willing to put themselves at risk for their "sisters."
In addition, the writers introduced a new clone character - the mysterious MK - and gave the "beauty professional" Krystal Goderitch a lot more to do this season. That was a big plus for me because Krystal brought just the right amount of levity to what was - on the whole - a pretty serious body of work. On top of that, the writers brought to life a truly evil woman who is out to do away with all the "sisters" to advance her own technology and seize control of the corporation that created them. Evie Cho is everything you want in a villain: She's beautiful, ruthless, and an A-level schemer.
The series just keeps getting better and better in my opinion despite the fact that the writers tend to kill off characters that I really enjoy watching. Still, that's not a terrible thing because the deaths are not simply gratuitous but advance the storyline. It's because they do that I am willing (well, almost...) to forgive the writers for getting rid of some of those characters.
Well plotted, brilliantly acted, and tightly directed, Season Four is another winner and I can't wait for Season Five.

From Ginger Snaps 2, up to this time of Orphan Black season 4, Tatiana Maslany is a master at her craft. Taking on multiple parts and multiple rolls, she is each and every one of her creations. So complete is her ability to convince us of absolute, in your face changes from one character to the next. That suspending disbelief is not an issue at all. She takes each of her Orphans to be separate and autonomous from the hive as a whole, while keeping the underlying bond of genetic clones always at the edge, bubbling just below the surface. It is a great ride. Good writing and rolls makes for a lot of the work done by actors to be more solid and believable than the same with poor material. Tatiana is a master of her art. I just do not know which of the Orphans I would fall for. She must be amazing to talk with. I would love to watch the making of one scene with multiple Orphans in it. I have watched the behind the scenes making of a few of these. But to follow her around from the beginning of a episode to the end. If I was 50 years younger I'd ask her for a date. Even if we sat and talked for an hour, I would have one hell of a check off on my bucket list. Bravo Tatiana, you are the actors actor, and holding yourself above the tabloid smut cannons only makes you more admirable. My daughter wants to be an actor... I tend to refer to you as what I hope she does with that desire. Tatiana must have a blast with all this great material. I'm hooked.

This series has me hook, line, and sinker.  I don't know if Tatiana Maslany has won any awards for her acting but she should. Her ability to portray a down and out hustler (Sarah), ditzy suburban soccer mom, cop, brilliant scientist, Eastern European psycho, cold hearted corporate honcho, manicurist, and, believe it or not, additional smaller roles, amazes me. Jordan Gavaris, in his role as Sarah's brother Felix, also gives a noteworthy performance.

Tatiana Maslany's supremely nuanced array of multiple-clone personas must rank as the finest acting performance within any TV series.  She deserves every award, as does the show as a whole.  Nothing else out there grapples so believably with the socio-moral nightmare of bio-tech driven by corporate malice.  The show's premise, that human destiny lies in the hands of unregulated lab techniciansperhaps even unbeknownst to us todayis far scarier than more blatantly futuristic sci-fi.  We already have the capacity, as MK's 'Dolly the Sheep'-masked-character reminds us, to make sheep of the human race.  Season 4 sets up the unmissable final season, coming next year.  Whatever you do, don't miss a single episode in this 5-season masterpiece!

The fourth season finds the Clone Club back at the beginning of the story - and Neolution looming large - as we learn about Beth Childs and what she had learned before she felt she had to commit suicide. We also meet M.K., a new clone who had been helping Beth and was, according to the Helsinki graphic novel, around even before that. M.K. has managed to simultaneously take herself off the grid and maintain serious cyberspying, and gathering information.

Into the mix is added Evie Cho who has replaced cloning with biotech in hopes of furthering Neolution's aims while saving her own life.

Meanwhile, Sarah, Alison, Cosima and Helena are facing different trials: Sarah has managed to lose brother Felix's confidence in her (while he's also found his biological sister, Adele); Cosima's research and trials have been thwarted; Alison and Donny are victims of a play by a crooked cop, and Helena is living in the wilds.

The plot is as convoluted as ever, though the best episodes are mostly based on single characters (one on Beth; one on Sarah's night of blowing off steam).

The writing remains at as high a level of quality as ever; the ideas developed are shocking and yet so completely plausible; the performances (including all six clones - Krystal is back and so close to the truth and yet so far away that it's amazing - by Tatiana Maslany) are terrific and the effects work is seamless.

For my money, Orphan Black is the best show on TV right now (it's more twisted than Mr. Robot and more compelling than Game of Thrones - though not by much).

Tatiana Maslany is the most incredible, refreshing, talented, beautiful, funny, and versatile actor I have ever seen or could ever dream up. This show is intense and thought-provoking, exciting, and tackles a lot of issues that might be too "sci-fi" for some people, although they probably aren't that far away from happening in 'real' life. But the real catch for me is basically just to see what Tatiana can do! For many of the scenes, there are multiple clones interacting with each other, but it is just Tatiana, acting to a stand-in. Then doing the scene as the next character, and the next, etc. She is doing the work of up to 5 people in the same scenes sometimes  - and then they have to splice everything together without any of us noticing a difference! You really believe in each character, she plays them with so much authenticity in every movement, accent, clothing style, facial expression, and she never misses anything, not even the tiniest little detail, about which character she's playing in every moment. And they love to throw crazy curve-balls out of nowhere, so I've learned to really watch it intensely. I get so wrapped up in this show, it kills me to only have 10 episodes a season!!!!

In almost any decent movie or TV series, there is one performance that is so natural, so comfortable, so convincing, that you don't think of it as a performance at all--you simply accept that character as a real person caught up in the events of the story.  It's rarely a lead performance, because stars carry too much baggage into each role.  I don't know how she does it, and I might not believe it if I hadn't seen it with my own eyes and heart, but Tatiana Maslany pulls off ten or so characterizations of that caliber in "Orphan Black."  As all the Leda clones, she is utterly convincing as genetically identical individuals raised in different cultures, different countries, different belief systems, economic strata, political conditions--all the elements of "nurture" that contribute to our being who we are.  When the clones interact with (and impersonate) each other on the screen, we don't see great performances or technical wizardry (both of which are there), we see Helena, Cosima, Sarah, Krystal, Rachel--and all the other "sestras."  We see them as real people, scrambling to understand and survive a dangerous and mystifying situation that is not of their making and mostly out of their control.  Brilliant stuff.  Don't miss it--but start at Season 1, Episode 1.

Having just watched the entirety of season four of Orphan Black in the span of a few days, I will say this was certainly a step in the right direction after what was a troublesome season three. We also get to know more about some of the clones that haven't been featured as much as the main few. Also we meet some new ones as well. There's plenty of humor, heartbreak and even some horror.

My only major complaint is that the show is hinting at some characters having psychic powers. In my opinion this is a realm which doesn't fit the "hard science" nature of Orphan Black and shouldn't be expanded upon.

I found season 4 of Orphan Black to be a bit disappointing.  It's hard to say what's wrong with without giving away what happens, but I'll just say it lacked a lot of the dark humour of past seasons, and the thriller aspect that really made the show so good.  Tatiana Maslany still does a brilliant job playing multiple characters, each with their own personality, but some of well at least in my eyes, more interesting characters, don't have a great deal of screen time. There really weren't any great new clones either, just one who wears a sheep mask and to be honest I just found a little annoying. The season starts off as well with an episode about Beth, we have a number of flashbacks throughout the rest of the season with Beth as well.  There is a worm in this season that's pretty cool but the plot doesn't really use it to it's full potential. Likewise we had potential for some great prison scenes but we barely even visit there.  There was a lot of phone ringtone sounds throughout each episode which was a bit annoying too.

Anyone else have a problem with episodes just suddenly stopping? I am aggravated by this, it has happened so many times on so many shows I watch regularly, Grimm, The Originals, Vikings, Teen Wolf, and Orphan Black. I really get into each season and episode and anxiously wait for the next episode and they suddenly stop coming in. I pay for Prime which I'm still getting screwed on seeing how Amazon only allows maybe the first 2,3 seasons to be free and every other season after that you have to pay. I'm about ready to cut Amazon off completely, the way I see it, with so many phone apps coming out where anyone can buy/sell, stream movies, play games, I don't need to hassle with Amazon any longer. Besides they don't care about the customer, anytime I need to speak with customer service there's no contact number to call, it's only email. I figure the reason they have email as customer service is so they can send back and automated response. I've complained about this numerous times and each time I receive the same response word for word, so that tells me they leave it up to a machine to deal with their customers.

Orphan Black is one of the few things in life I get really, really excited about. Season 4 does not disappoint: the intrigue thickens, new clones and some old favorites, and just enough shocking twists to keep things interesting without jumping the shark. The acting and the meta-acting are fabulous fabulous fabulous (are you listening, Emmy committee??). I'm just sad to have to wait until next year for more.

Sarah Manning and her clone-sisters have defeated the threat of an illegal attempt to create an army of cloned soldiers, and it seems like maybe they might be able to get back to their lives. But the Neolutionists, who want to expand genetic engineering far beyond mere cloning, have other plans. Sarah and her friends, aided by an enigmatic newcomer known as "MK", are threatened by different factions within the Neolutionist movement and have to face the possibility of making a deal with the devil just to survive.

The first three seasons of Orphan Black were excellent, with the writers showing unusual self-awareness by slimming down a potentially confusing morass of subplots and factions in the third season to a much more straightforward conflict. The fourth season sees this conflict resolved and a whole new storyline begun, but one very much rooted in what came before. The Neolutionists, an opposing faction established in the first season but soon superseded by other groups, return to prominence and the show goes back into its roots by exploring the character of Beth Childs in greater depth. This is also gives supporting characters like Art (who was a little lost in the third season) more to do.

This results in some focused, dramatically-accomplished storytelling. One episode focuses almost entirely on Beth's life as she discovered she was a clone, meeting Allison and Cosima and then the shadowy MK, with events building to the tragic and inevitable end we are already aware of from the opening seconds of the whole series. Tatiana Maslany is so great in her multiple roles that it feels like we've gone beyond redundant in mentioning it, but she somehow manages to up her game even further in the fourth season with both her portrayal of the doomed Beth and also in the present day, particularly her performance as Cosmia where she adds more nuance, depth and tragedy than ever before.

The fourth season risks getting heavy at times, so as usual relies on the screamingly dysfunctional (and dystopian) domestic adventures of Allison and Donnie Hendricks to draw things back in with jet-black humour. This season they also do a great job of involving Allison and Donnie more in the main storylines (in Season 3 it felt like they were making their own spin-off in the context of the larger show) and tonally varying things up a bit to make things more interesting. Donnie and Felix posing as a gay couple looking to have a baby might be the funniest storyline the show has ever done, especially as Felix reels in Donnie's stereotypical performance. Felix, who also got a little lost in the mix in Season 3, gets more to do this year as he embarks on his own quest to find his biological family. We get a lot more insight and empathy into the "villains" of the show this year as well.

Season 4 doesn't really falter at all, although some fans will bemoan a distinct lack of screen-time for Helena (although when she does return, she makes it felt in her own inimitable style) and the total absence of Cal (Michael Huisman possibly busy filming Game of Thrones). Particularly brilliant is the ending, which sets us up with a new villain who is actually an old one: Orphan Black and Game of Thrones have both realised that there is nothing more satisfying than having your ultimate main bad guy as someone you've gotten to know already over multiple years and set up accordingly. Things are set up for what will hopefully be an exhilarating showdown in the final season next year.

Orphan Black's fourth season (*****) sees the show somehow get even better than it was previously. Even in a golden age of television, it is entirely possible that this little SF show from Canada might be the very best thing on TV at the moment.

I was hooked on this show from the first five minutes of season one (the train platform scene!).  I went on to watch the whole first season in one sitting that went from evening to night to morning.  I have been watching TV since the 1960s and this is hands down my favourite programme ever.

If it weren't for lead actress Tatiana Maslany it would be a great show.  All aspects -- writing, direction, special effects, cinematography, music etc -- are excellent, and the brilliant supporting cast (Jordan Gavaris, Evelyn Brochu, Maria Doyle Kennedy, Kristian Bruun, Kevin Hanchard et al) all give 100% committed performances throughout.

But when you factor in Maslany's performances, the whole thing is lifted to another level.  She has created seven main characters plus numerous lesser ones, and each one is distinct, fully realised and compelling.  She frequently plays one character interacting with another (and sometimes three or four), so convincingly that you completely forget she has filmed the scene in separate takes hours apart, talking to empty space, before the technical wizards put the scene together.  On occasions she plays one character imitating another (i.e. herself imitating herself!), and the viewer can see subtle elements of the imitating character showing through in the imitated.  She combines incredible technical ability with great emotional truth not to mention hilarious comic delivery as Alison, Helena and Krystal (my favourite).  She probably should have had three Emmy awards already, but somehow she has got even better in this fourth Season, and the award is long overdue.

Season Four goes back to the beginning after the spiralling conspiracies of seasons 1-3.  Episode 1 finally puts the spotlight on Beth, whose suicide kicked the whole thing off, and Tatiana Maslany's performance reaches new heights as the detective's life unravels, faced with the truth about her origin, the people who threaten her and her sisters, her escalating drug use, and her troubled relationships.  The tension and drama are maintained throughout the ten episodes, with particular highlights being the emotional climax of episode 6, followed by a long dark night of the soul for at least two characters in episode 7, and a brutal fight between Maslany and herself - as well as a long-awaited reunion - in episode 10.

It's magnificent stuff.  The only negative is that there will only be one more Season after this, but roll on 2017!

The writing got a little tired this season and the series has become fairly formulaic (defeat the big bad leader of the secretive shadowy conspiracy group doing horrible things, only to realize what you *didn't* know is that the *real* big bad is actually *this* person who is part of an even *secreter* shadowy conspiracy group! And they're doing much *worse* horrible things! Hey let's throw a new clone or two into the mix for funsies. Rinse. Repeat.) Also the one big devastating thing that happened this season happened because clone club decided to become temporarily idiotic for no apparent reason. You really don't think to keep a few tissue samples back at the lab just in case, or back up your data to an external hard drive? Really. Jesus that's dumb. The Sestras have had ample opportunity to learn better than that by now.

But I keep watching because Tatiana Maslany is mesmerizing as [f-bomb redacted], and as an actor myself, I appreciate and am mad jealous of the chops required to play all these different people. My brain really gets tricked into thinking there are a good dozen separate actresses running around with that exact face... And then when she plays one clone doing an impression of another, and the degree of accuracy matches up with that character's likely skill level at impersonation (I.e. Con artist Sarah is way better at pretending to be other clones like Rachel or Crystal than Cosima is at pretending to be Allison)? Mind blown.

I hear some of her accents, particularly the Ukrainian one, leave something to be desired by native speakers. But at least she keeps them consistent. The accents don't change over time or bleed between characters. That is really impressive.

Also, can somebody please address what ever happened to Marion Bowles? Seriously. She had potential.

The writing and acting is superb in this Canadian sci fi series about human cloning.  Lead actress Tatiana Maslany is so good that when she plays different clone characters you forget it is the same actress!  She has created at least 6 major characters and many more minor ones, all with different personalities, voices, mannerisms, accents, not to mention hair & makeup. The show is a technical marvel too as Tatiana as conflicted cop Beth, punk rocker Sarah, Ukrainian assassin Helena, soccer mom Alison,  brilliant scientist Cosima, evil Rachel, and valley girl beautician Crystal interact with each other, 2 or 3 in the same scene. Terrific supporting cast includes the amazing and amusing Jordan Gavaris. Season 4 reins in some of the religious cult craziness of previous seasons and builds to a very action-packed finale.

Simply sublime.  A magnificent accomplishment, ORPHAN BLACK quickly won me over as one of the greatest TV series I have ever  seen.  Two episodes into season 1, I was intrigued.  At the 4th episode I was arrested and disarmed completely.  Like falling in love.  Dreadfully wrenching, delightfully mischievous, marvelously engineered, delicately touching, profoundly passionate, and so beautifully wrought, it always -- always -- leaves me craving more.  One episode per week is not fast enough.  Ten episodes per season is just not enough, period.  The withdrawal kills me.  Tatiana Maslany, in ten distinct roles (so far), several often (incredibly) interacting in the same scenes, is not just astonishing, but is breathtaking.  The sheer range and depth of her performances reaches so far beyond any map of skill or talent that I consider her the greatest and most underrated actress I've ever been blessed to watch.  ORPHAN BLACK has no comparisons.  It works on so many levels, plays in so many genres, that it integrates into an astonishing mirror on humanity.  (To my fellow clone-addicts, keep sharing the passion -- Tatiana needs her Golden Globe, Emmy, Oscar.  NOW.)  I am so grateful that I discovered this series in my searches on Amazon!

I haven't seen yet any connecting of the dots between the bigotry and the eugenics inspired part of the story line, which is one of the things that has appealed to me since the first season. The idea that a person can declare another his or her property is one I can relate to from a racial perspective, but the writers have yet to make that connection. I hope they do eventually.

That said, I have been watching since the first season and I plan to continue doing so. It's one of the few shows I look forward to every week. For a time, I was afraid the series' story line would unravel, in its fourth season, as so many others have. But it didn't, not really, and all those other enviable aspects of the production, not the least the acting, tend to tighten up whatever has become looser. Consider, for example, Episode 8 of Season 4, in which Allison's earnest rehearsal of the church production of "Jesus Christ Superstar" is intercut with her husband Donny's being threatened --- tortured, really --- by a Neolutionist thug who's imprisoned with him. Brilliant, and emotionally satisfying. Let me recommend also something relatively new to me: the "After" sessions, in which cast members and series creators get to talk about what they do, and there are revelations of "set secrets". I've seen this device used as tags on other series, e.g., "The Walking Dead", but in the case of "Orphan Black" it is, as is the show itself, markedly more intelligent.

Love, Love, Love this show!
Tatiana Maslany is a master at playing all the different clones, all with their unique personalities and quirks. She does this so well you can even tell when one clone is impersonating another, truly inspiring. The story of Sarah takes us on a never ending journey as she and her sisters learn about where they came from, why, who created them and why. Sarah's foster brother and side kick, Felix is a joy to watch and as season 4 shows him coming into his own, along with more about Beth, the sister who in a way set the whole journey into motion.
The co-stars and supporting cast are also brilliant and the writers are imaginative without going over the top. Each episode is filled with intrigue, love, compassion and questions, many questions, and some answers. It is also very fast paced, at the end of each episode I'm always surprised that the 40+minutes is already flown by.
My only complaint is that a season is only 10 episodes in length, so in the weeks leading up to a new season I binge watch the series from the beginning and never tire or watching, seeing, learning and discovering something new with each watch and new understanding of the story line.
If you haven't watched this yet I recommend you do so, it's an interesting, intriguing story line that will pull you in in the first 10 minutes.

I loved the first three seasons, but it seems like the episodes in season 4 are not cohesive.  Also, I feel that the writers don't really know where to go with the characters, so they just keep putting them in increasingly outrageous situations.

A disappointing season so far (ep. 5).  The bug in the cheek appears to be a MacGuffin and the plots have become even more twisted and confusing than previous seasons (which is saying a lot since even previous seasons required effort to follow).  Also, we need at least one throwaway episode to lighten the excessively heavy tone this season.

I think the confusion has also taken its toll on viewership.  While Seasons 2 and 3 averaged 0.5 million viewers per episode, Season 4 is more like half that.  I'm not so sure that level of viewership supports continuation to Season 5.  Hopefully, the writers can pull a rabbit out of their hats for the last half of the season.

Why do I love this series? Because it has EVERYTHING! It is funny, serious, scientific, science fiction, reality, fantasy, shocking, devastating, heartwarming and heartbreaking. It has danger, action, love, hate, sadness, happiness, fun, fear, illness, miracles, death, life, murder, mystery and oh did I forget to mention sex?...Has it all and one Amazing Actress, who plays several parts as if she is a different actress for each, so much I forget I am watching one person. Orphan Black continues to be such an original show that not enough people are watching. I just finished the last season and it was very entertaining watching Tatiana play all of the clone sisters though some were much better than others you're never seeing one long enough thats its a problem. The plot is about clones, competing forces, issues and the ever present family and/or domestic crisis. A very good supporting cast keeps it together and if theres a fault it would be the humor is not always present but when it is its a real boost to the show. The last season seemed rushed, over the top and pretty devoid of humor. Its a good sci-fi thriller and through the course of the show it was sometimes hard to tell the same person was playing all the roles because the transformations were so good. Overall, it was a 4-star series but the last one is a real push to give it 3-stars. There are a few characters that I found to be annoying and there was much too much of them toward the end. If nothing else, it was worth it just for the uniqueness of the plot and how well it was done by Tatiana. It took us four years to see the entire series so Im copping out with the same review for each because my mind is too blurry to address each one specifically and if you like the first one you will watch the others despite what anyone has to say about it.
